1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,480
This host has nothing installed, but Docker.

2
00:00:02,480 --> 00:00:05,400
No Kubernetes, no F5 tooling.

3
00:00:05,400 --> 00:00:06,700
In the next five minutes,

4
00:00:06,700 --> 00:00:09,920
Claude Code will deploy a full F5 BIG-IP Next

5
00:00:09,920 --> 00:00:11,440
for Kubernetes stack

6
00:00:11,440 --> 00:00:13,680
and fix the problems it hits along the way.

7
00:00:14,680 --> 00:00:17,000
One Go binary drives everything.

8
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:18,700
We build and install it,

9
00:00:18,700 --> 00:00:20,040
then ask it to check the host.

10
00:00:20,040 --> 00:00:22,320
ocibnkctl doctor inspects the runtime,

11
00:00:22,320 --> 00:00:25,360
kubectl, helm, and the CPU and memory floor.

12
00:00:25,360 --> 00:00:26,880
Here it finds a missing tool

13
00:00:26,880 --> 00:00:29,120
and prints the exact, operating-system-

14
00:00:29,120 --> 00:00:31,120
aware command to install it.

15
00:00:31,120 --> 00:00:33,040
Claude offers to run that for us.

16
00:00:33,040 --> 00:00:34,880
This is the pattern for the whole demo.

17
00:00:34,880 --> 00:00:36,320
The tool reports the truth.

18
00:00:36,320 --> 00:00:37,620
The agent acts on it.

19
00:00:38,600 --> 00:00:41,040
Every deployment lives in a self-contained folder

20
00:00:41,040 --> 00:00:44,680
called a PoC. ocibnkctl init demo scaffolds it.

21
00:00:44,680 --> 00:00:47,680
Inside: poc.yaml, the single source of truth;

22
00:00:47,680 --> 00:00:50,320
AGENTS.md, the operating manual Claude reads first;
a gitignored keys folder for secrets.

23
00:00:50,320 --> 00:00:53,400
The agent always reads poc.yaml before it acts.

24
00:00:54,360 --> 00:00:56,160
The deploy needs two customer secrets

25
00:00:56,160 --> 00:00:58,000
from F5's license portal.

26
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:01,240
A TEEM activation token, the JWT,

27
00:01:01,240 --> 00:01:04,800
and a FAR image-pull tarball for the F5 registry.

28
00:01:04,800 --> 00:01:06,520
Without them, the deploy stops

29
00:01:06,520 --> 00:01:08,560
and tells us exactly what's missing.

30
00:01:08,560 --> 00:01:10,800
Claude explains where each one comes from,

31
00:01:10,800 --> 00:01:12,920
and we drop them into the keys folder.

32
00:01:12,920 --> 00:01:14,840
We never print their contents.

33
00:01:14,840 --> 00:01:17,600
They stay out of the journal and out of every report.

34
00:01:18,560 --> 00:01:19,820
Now the payload.

35
00:01:19,820 --> 00:01:22,540
One command runs the whole pipeline: validate,

36
00:01:22,540 --> 00:01:23,760
bring up a two-node k3s cluster

37
00:01:23,760 --> 00:01:26,240
directly as Docker containers,

38
00:01:26,240 --> 00:01:29,320
install cert-manager and the F5 FLO chart,

39
00:01:29,320 --> 00:01:32,160
then the CNE instance with TMM in demo mode.

40
00:01:32,160 --> 00:01:34,720
The first four phases finish in about a minute.

41
00:01:34,720 --> 00:01:37,880
The last one, the F5 control plane reconciling,

42
00:01:37,880 --> 00:01:40,660
takes a few minutes more, which we've sped up here.

43
00:01:40,660 --> 00:01:41,960
With a warm image cache,

44
00:01:41,960 --> 00:01:44,840
the whole deploy is about five and a half minutes.

45
00:01:44,840 --> 00:01:48,260
The first run, pulling images, is closer to fifteen.

46
00:01:48,260 --> 00:01:51,380
Watch the pods schedule and turn ready in k9s,

47
00:01:51,380 --> 00:01:53,660
thirty of them across two nodes.

48
00:01:54,560 --> 00:01:58,060
No kind, no k3d, no third-party orchestrator,

49
00:01:58,060 --> 00:01:59,040
just Docker.

50
00:02:00,020 --> 00:02:01,860
Real deployments hit snags.

51
00:02:01,860 --> 00:02:03,780
Here a pod is stuck Pending.

52
00:02:03,780 --> 00:02:04,940
Instead of guessing,

53
00:02:04,940 --> 00:02:08,300
Claude runs doctor and reads the pod's events and logs,

54
00:02:08,300 --> 00:02:10,540
then names the cause in plain language

55
00:02:10,540 --> 00:02:12,240
and proposes the fix.

56
00:02:12,240 --> 00:02:15,780
The agent isn't just typing commands, it's diagnosing.

57
00:02:16,740 --> 00:02:19,660
To prove it works, we run the scenario suite.

58
00:02:19,660 --> 00:02:22,060
Each one maps to an F5 how-to article,

59
00:02:22,060 --> 00:02:24,220
twelve of twelve pass green.

60
00:02:24,220 --> 00:02:25,940
And because cluster up installed

61
00:02:25,940 --> 00:02:27,260
the kubeconfig for us,

62
00:02:27,260 --> 00:02:30,500
kubectl and k9s talk to the cluster directly.

63
00:02:30,500 --> 00:02:32,880
Browse the whole F5 stack live.

64
00:02:33,840 --> 00:02:35,760
One command tears it all down.

65
00:02:35,760 --> 00:02:37,420
Containers, network,

66
00:02:37,420 --> 00:02:40,600
and it even restores your original kubeconfig from backup.

67
00:02:40,600 --> 00:02:44,080
A full F5 BIG-IP Next for Kubernetes deployment

68
00:02:44,080 --> 00:02:47,520
on plain Docker, driven end to end by Claude Code.

69
00:02:47,520 --> 00:02:50,860
The tool is on GitHub at mwiget slash ocibnkctl.
